---js
const layout = "layouts/home.njk";
const title = "Software Architecture & Codebase Review — Berlin";
const description = "Honest, scoped software architecture and codebase review in Berlin. Two-week engagement, decision-grade deliverable: what's load-bearing, what's rot, what's worth the rewrite.";
const sitemap = { priority: "0.9", changefreq: "monthly" };
---
{% css %}
@layer page {
	{% include "css/landing.css" %}
}
{% endcss %}

<article class="landing">
	<nav class="landing-crumbs" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
		<a href="/">Home</a>
		<span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">/</span>
		<a href="/freelance-tech-lead-berlin/">Freelance</a>
		<span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">/</span>
		<span aria-current="page">Architecture &amp; codebase review</span>
	</nav>

	<header class="landing-hero">
		<p class="landing-eyebrow">Matt Richards &middot; Berlin</p>
		<h1>Software architecture &amp; codebase <em>review.</em></h1>
		<p class="lede">An honest, senior read on what's load-bearing, what's rot, and what's worth the rewrite. Scoped, written up, handed over &mdash; a decision-grade document you can actually use. Berlin, EU, remote.</p>
		<div class="landing-meta">
			<a class="eyebrow-link" href="/contact">Request a review</a>
			<span class="landing-locator"><span class="online-dot" aria-hidden="true"></span>Currently open to new work</span>
		</div>
	</header>

	<section class="landing-services" aria-label="What an architecture review looks like">
		<div class="service">
			<span class="service-kicker">&sect; 01</span>
			<h2 class="service-head">Honest read</h2>
			<p class="service-body">No consulting theatre. A senior engineer reading your codebase the way you would, if you had a month to stare at it.</p>
		</div>
		<div class="service">
			<span class="service-kicker">&sect; 02</span>
			<h2 class="service-head">Scoped deliverable</h2>
			<p class="service-body">A written review, a read-out with the team, a prioritised list of what to do next. Two weeks. Scoped, written up, handed over. No open-ended scope creep.</p>
		</div>
		<div class="service">
			<span class="service-kicker">&sect; 03</span>
			<h2 class="service-head">Decision support</h2>
			<p class="service-body">Rewrite or refactor? Monolith or split? Buy or build? The call is yours; the second opinion is mine &mdash; with receipts.</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="landing-section">
		<h2><span class="ix">&sect; 04 &mdash; What you get</span>A document you can act on</h2>
		<div class="landing-body">
			<p>A codebase review earns its keep when it tells you something you couldn't see from inside. The deliverable is shaped for the people who'll read it &mdash; engineers, leadership, investors &mdash; not as a box-ticking exercise.</p>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Executive summary</strong> &mdash; one page. The headline read on health, risk and next best move.</li>
				<li><strong>Architecture diagram</strong> &mdash; what's actually in the system, not what the wiki thinks is in the system.</li>
				<li><strong>Risk register</strong> &mdash; the parts that will bite you, ranked by likelihood and blast radius.</li>
				<li><strong>Prioritised backlog</strong> &mdash; concrete, sized items. What to do first, what to defer, what to stop doing.</li>
				<li><strong>Read-out</strong> &mdash; a working session with your team. Questions answered. Disagreements welcome.</li>
			</ul>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="landing-section">
		<h2><span class="ix">&sect; 05 &mdash; When it helps</span>The moments a second read pays off</h2>
		<div class="landing-body">
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Pre-raise or pre-sale diligence</strong> &mdash; you want a clean story before investors or acquirers bring their own.</li>
				<li><strong>New engineering lead starting</strong> &mdash; ninety days in, with an independent map of the terrain.</li>
				<li><strong>Rewrite or refactor?</strong> &mdash; the quarterly debate your team can't settle. A grounded outside take.</li>
				<li><strong>Post-acquisition landing</strong> &mdash; you bought a codebase. Now you have to live in it.</li>
				<li><strong>Scaling pain</strong> &mdash; things that worked at 10 engineers are breaking at 40. Where the cracks are.</li>
			</ul>
			<p>Twenty years across product engineering and leadership, platform-first. I've written, shipped and inherited enough codebases to tell rot from rough edges. <a href="/about">More about how I work &rarr;</a></p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="landing-related" aria-label="Related services">
		<h2>Related services</h2>
		<ul class="landing-related-list">
			<li><a href="/fractional-engineering-lead-berlin/">Fractional engineering lead, Berlin</a><span class="sub">Strategy, team shape, mentorship</span></li>
			<li><a href="/ai-for-engineering-teams-berlin/">AI for engineering teams</a><span class="sub">Workflows, guardrails, team health</span></li>
			<li><a href="/freelance-tech-lead-berlin/">Freelance tech lead, Berlin</a><span class="sub">Hands-on technical leadership</span></li>
		</ul>
	</section>

	<section class="landing-next" aria-label="Where to go next">
		<div class="next">
			<span class="next-kicker">Background</span>
			<h3>About</h3>
			<p>Twenty years, two sides of the bench: product engineering and engineering leadership.</p>
			<a class="cta" href="/about">Read the long version</a>
		</div>
		<div class="next">
			<span class="next-kicker">Writing</span>
			<h3>Words</h3>
			<p>Notes on craft, leadership, and the age of AI. The archive &mdash; dated, unvarnished.</p>
			<a class="cta" href="/words">Open the archive</a>
		</div>
		<div class="next">
			<span class="next-kicker">Work together</span>
			<h3>Contact</h3>
			<p>Email, Signal, or the form. Tell me what you're building and what's in the way.</p>
			<a class="cta" href="/contact">Get in touch</a>
		</div>
	</section>
</article>

<script type="application/ld+json">
